## üéØ Clinical Applications

### Primary Pattern & Manifestations
**Pattern**: Liver and kidney yin deficiency with eye problems and visual disturbances
**Key Symptoms**: Blurred vision, dry eyes, eye fatigue, night blindness, photophobia, dizziness, tinnitus, lower back pain, dry mouth, hot flashes, insomnia
**Tongue**: Red with little coating
**Pulse**: Thready and rapid

### Secondary Applications
- Age-related macular degeneration
- Diabetic retinopathy (early stages)
- Chronic dry eye syndrome
- Computer vision syndrome
- Glaucoma support (as adjunct)
- Menopausal eye symptoms

### Modern Clinical Uses
- Age-related macular degeneration and retinal disorders
- Diabetic retinopathy and metabolic eye disease
- Chronic dry eye syndrome and meibomian gland dysfunction
- Computer eye strain and digital eye fatigue
- Glaucoma and elevated intraocular pressure (adjunct therapy)
- Cataract prevention and eye aging

## üìù Therapeutic Actions
**Primary**: Nourish kidney yin, brighten eyes, benefit liver and kidney

**Secondary**: Improve vision, reduce eye inflammation, support retinal health, prevent eye aging

## üîÑ Modifications & Variations

### Common Additions
| Condition | Add Herbs | Rationale |
|-----------|-----------|-----------|
| Severe eye dryness | Bai Shao + Gan Cao | Enhanced yin nourishing and moistening |
| Retinal problems | Dan Shen + Hong Hua | Improve retinal circulation |
| High eye pressure | Xia Ku Cao + Jue Ming Zi | Reduce intraocular pressure |
| Night blindness | Ye Ming Sha + Gu Jing Cao | Specific for night vision |

### Classical Variations
- **Liu Wei Di Huang Wan**: Without Gou Qi Zi and Ju Hua (general kidney yin)
- **Zhi Bai Di Huang Wan**: Replace eye herbs with Zhi Mu + Huang Bai for heat
- **Ming Mu Di Huang Wan**: Enhanced version with more eye-specific herbs

### Modern Modifications
- For macular degeneration: Add Dan Shen and Shan Zha
- For diabetic retinopathy: Add Huang Qi and Danshen
- For glaucoma: Add Xia Ku Cao and Che Qian Zi

